Multiple Linear Regression

Part I: Practice Questions

  1. A large national grocery retailer tracks productivity and cost of its facilities closely. The data in the grocery.txt file were obtained from a single distribution center for a one year period. Each data point for each variable represents one week of activity. The variables included are the number of cases shipped (\(X_1\)), the indirect costs of the total labor hours as a percentage (\(X_2\)), a qualitative predictor called holiday that is called in one of the week has a holy day and zero otherwise (\(X_3\)), and the total labor hours (\(Y\)).

    library(ggplot2)
    ## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.6.2
    library(faraway)
grocery <- read.table("grocery.txt", header=FALSE) 
names(grocery) <- c("Y", "X1", "X2", "X3") 
grocery.full = lm(Y~., data=grocery) 
summary(grocery.full)

    1. Identify any outlying \(Y\) observations. Use the Bonferroni outlier test procedure with \(\alpha=.05\). State decision rule and conclusion.

      jackknife=rstudent(grocery.full)
n = dim(grocery)[1]
p = 4 #dim(grocery)[2]
qt(.05/(2*n), n-p-1)
      ## [1] -3.52308

      All of the residuals in absolute value are smaller than 3.52308. So, there are no outliers in this case.

    2. Obtain the diagonal elements of the hat matrix. Identify any high leverage points. If any, are they good or bad?

      diag_hat = lm.influence(grocery.full)$hat
diag_hat[diag_hat>(2*p/n)]
      ##         3         5        16        21        22        43        44        48 
## 0.2188773 0.2063282 0.2554249 0.1936047 0.2577199 0.2868586 0.2200236 0.2817766

      Points 3,5,16,21,22,43,44,48 are all high leverage points.

      halfnorm(diag_hat, 2, ylab="Leverages")

      Based on the plot, we can say that all of these points have their \(y\) coordinate shifted from the line which means that they are all bad high leverage points.

    3. Cases 16, 22, 43, and 48 appear to be outlying \(X\) observations, and cases 10, 32, 38, and 40 appear to be outlying \(Y\) observations. Obtain the Cooks distance values for each of these cases to assess their influence. What do you conclude?

      cook = cooks.distance(grocery.full) 
plot(cook)

      c(cook[16], cook[22], cook[43], cook[48])
      ##           16           22           43           48 
## 0.0768950835 0.0007746088 0.0792193145 0.0054988670
      c(cook[10], cook[32], cook[38], cook[40])
      ##         10         32         38         40 
## 0.04935012 0.09975974 0.03463803 0.03649915

      Their Cooks is much less than 1, so there are no outlying observations in this data.

Part II: Homework Questions

The whitewines.csv data set contains information related to white variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. Specifically, we have recorded the following information:

  1. fixed acidity, (b) volatile acidity, (c) citric acid, (d) residual sugar, (e) chlorides , (f) free sulfur dioxide, (g) total sulfur dioxide, (h) density, (i) pH, (j) sulphates, (k) alcohol, (l) quality (score between 0 and 10)

In this homework, our goal is to explain the relationship between alcohol level (dependent variable) and residual sugar, pH, density and fixed acidity.

whitewines = read.csv("whitewines.csv", sep = ";")

  1. Identify any outlying \(Y\) observations. Use the Bonferroni outlier test procedure with \(\alpha=.05\). State decision rule and conclusion.

    full_wine = lm(alcohol ~ residual.sugar + pH + density + fixed.acidity, data = whitewines)
n = dim(whitewines)[1]
p=5
qt(.05/(2*n), n-p-1)
    ## [1] -4.417336
    wine.resid = rstudent(full_wine) 
sort(abs(wine.resid), decreasing = TRUE)[1:10]
    ##      2782      3902      1527      1654      1664      1418      2732      3620 
## 43.513422  8.425736  7.325843  6.464412  6.464412  4.103559  4.093453  4.068846 
##      3624      2731 
##  4.068846  4.060125
    We start by fitting the full model. Then, we extract the studentized residuals needed to perform the Bonferroni outlier test. We compute the t-distribution value with degrees of freedom \(n-p-1\). We observe that the 5 highest values of the residuals are greater (in absolute value) than 4.42, which means that we have 5 outliers, that is observations in rows 2782, 3902, 1527, 1654, 1664.

  2. Obtain the diagonal elements of the hat matrix and identify any high leverage points. If any, are they good or bad?

    We use the lm.influence function to compute the leverages (i.e.the diagonal elements of the hat matrix). 

    lev = lm.influence(full_wine)$hat 
head(lev)
    ##            1            2            3            4            5            6 
## 0.0019801090 0.0010926160 0.0009988590 0.0002865956 0.0002865956 0.0009988590
    leverages = lev[lev>(2*p/n)] 
head(leverages)
    ##          15          32          73          99         116         170 
## 0.002069166 0.002601884 0.002970866 0.003260806 0.002446706 0.003052161

    We observe that we have many high leverage points. In fact, we find that about 5% of the observations are high leverage points. 

    length(leverages) / n
    ## [1] 0.05042875
     library(faraway)
halfnorm(lev, 6, labs=as.character(1:length(lev)), ylab = "Leverages")

    Using the half-norm plot, we find that we have at least two bad high leverage points, i.e.observations 1527 and 2782.

  3. Use Cooks distance to investigate whether there are any high influential points. What do you conclude?

    cooks = cooks.distance(full_wine) 
sort(cooks, decreasing = TRUE)[1:10]
    ##         2782         1527         1654         1664         3902         3620 
## 14.232508181  0.247248953  0.053465084  0.053465084  0.031188148  0.011067253 
##         3624         2731         1952         2732 
##  0.011067253  0.007939572  0.007433765  0.006609749

    Using our rule of thumb, we only have one highly influential observation (an obs with cooks distance greater than 1), observation 2782.

  4. Calculate Cooks distance \(D_i\) for each case and prepare an index plot. Are any cases influential according to this measure?

    halfnorm(cooks, 6, labs=as.character(1:length(cooks)), ylab = "Cooks distances")

    Our previous conclusion is also reached by looking at the halfnormal plot.

  5. Predict the amount of alcohol of a white wine with residual.sugar = 1.7 , pH = 3, density = 1, fixed.acidity = 6.3 with an appropriate 95% confidence interval.

    predict( full_wine, data.frame( residual.sugar = 1.7, pH = 3, density = 1, fixed.acidity = 6.3), level = .95, interval = "confidence")
    ##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 4.533544 4.440764 4.626325

  6. Predict the amount of alcohol of a white wine with residual.sugar = 67 , pH = 4, density = 1.1, fixed.acidity = 15 with an appropriate 95% prediction interval.

    predict( full_wine, data.frame( residual.sugar = 67, pH = 4, density = 1.1, fixed.acidity = 15),level = .95,interval = "prediction")
    ##         fit       lwr       upr
## 1 -41.40047 -42.52562 -40.27533

    We observe that this interval is negative which might seem wrong. Mathematically, the calculations are correct. However, statistically in order to obtain this interval we did an extrapolation, since the values of the predictors are all outside the range of the values that we have already observed.

  7. Construct a 95% confidence region for the slope coefficients of pH and density. What do you conclude about the statistical significance of \(\beta_{pH}\) and \(\beta_{density}\)?

    library(ellipse)
    ## Warning: package 'ellipse' was built under R version 3.6.2
    ## 
## Attaching package: 'ellipse'
    ## The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':
## 
##     pairs
    library(ggplot2)
CR95 = ellipse(full_wine, c(3,4), level = .95) 
    ggplot(data = as.data.frame(CR95), aes(x = pH, y = density)) + 
  geom_path(col = "red", size = 1.5)

    The point (0,0) is not included in the confidence region which means that at least one of the betas is not equal to zero, or in other words at least one of the variables pH or density is statistically significant.

  8. Regress alcohol against fixed acidity and construct a 95% simultaneous confidence band for the fitted regression line.

    In the following examples, we fit a SLR model with alcohol as the response and fixed.acidity as the predictor. 

    wine.slr = lm(alcohol ~ fixed.acidity, data = whitewines) 
summary(wine.slr)
    ## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = alcohol ~ fixed.acidity, data = whitewines)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.9823 -1.0768 -0.1356  0.8699  3.6056 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   11.72264    0.14289  82.041   <2e-16 ***
## fixed.acidity -0.17628    0.02069  -8.521   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.222 on 4896 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.01461,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.01441 
## F-statistic:  72.6 on 1 and 4896 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

    We will construct step-by-step the confidence band as it is shown in Lecture 7, slide 17.

    The \(\hat{r}\) term is

    estimates = summary(wine.slr)$coefficients[1, 1] + summary(wine.slr)$coefficients[2,1]*whitewines[,1]

    while term \(c\) computes as:

    c = sqrt(2 * qf(.05, 2, n - 2, lower.tail = FALSE))

    Finally, we compute the estimated \(\sigma\), ie. \(\hat{\sigma}\):

    sigma = summary(wine.slr)$sigma * sqrt((1/n) +((whitewines[,1] - mean(whitewines[,1]))^2)/sum((whitewines[, 1]-mean(whitewines[,1]))^2))

    We combine the above the estimator, lower and upper bounds in a data frame:

    confidence.band = cbind(estimates, lower = estimates - c*sigma, upper = estimates + c*sigma)
head(confidence.band)                                                 
    ##      estimates    lower    upper
## [1,]  10.48867 10.44530 10.53204
## [2,]  10.61207 10.56091 10.66322
## [3,]  10.29476 10.21856 10.37095
## [4,]  10.45341 10.40723 10.49959
## [5,]  10.45341 10.40723 10.49959
## [6,]  10.29476 10.21856 10.37095

  9. Plot the raw data corresponding to question (h), fitted regression line, 95% point-wise confidence intervals and 95% confidence band calculated in (h). What do you observe?

    The following chunk of code computes the pointwise confidence intervals according to lecture 7 again. Note that the point estimates are the same as well as the standard error. What changes is the multiplier.

    t = qt(.025, n-2)
pointwise.interval = cbind(estimates, lower = estimates + t*sigma, upper = estimates - t*sigma) 
head(pointwise.interval)
    ##      estimates    lower    upper
## [1,]  10.48867 10.45394 10.52339
## [2,]  10.61207 10.57111 10.65302
## [3,]  10.29476 10.23375 10.35577
## [4,]  10.45341 10.41644 10.49039
## [5,]  10.45341 10.41644 10.49039
## [6,]  10.29476 10.23375 10.35577

    Finally, we plot together: the raw data, regression line (green), confidence band (blue), pointwise intervals (magenta):

    ggplot(data = whitewines, aes(x=fixed.acidity, y = alcohol)) + 
  geom_point(col = "darkblue", pch = 10) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y~x, col="green") + 
  geom_line(aes(y=confidence.band[,2]), col = "blue",  linetype=3) +
  geom_line(aes(y=confidence.band[,3]), col = "blue", linetype=3) +
  geom_line(aes(y=pointwise.interval[,2]), col = "magenta",   linetype=4) +
  geom_line(aes(y=pointwise.interval[,3]), col = "magenta",   linetype=5)

    As we expected, the confidence band is slightly wider than the pointwise intervals.
